The syllable in question is common to the word Tcut-oucs, Teutonicus, Theod- c'ccus, teudiscua, tout-iscus, teu-ele, duit-isles, liat-cclcc, deul-sch whilst the word Dect-scd means German. As the Teut-oucs were Germane, so were the Cimbri also. Now this line of argument is set aside hythe circumstance that the syllable Teut· in Paul-oues and Teutonicus, as the names of the con- federates of the cimbri, is wholly unconnected with the Teut- in theod-iscus, and Dect-scd. This is fully shown by Grimm in his dissertation on the words Germou and Dutch. In its oldest form the latter word meant populor, sational, ecrou- cucan- it was an adjective applied to the oulyunoupuc, or the vernacular German, iu oppositiou to the Latin. In the tenth century the secondary form Tcut-ouicus came in vogue even with German writers. Whether this arose out of imitation of the Latin form Romauicc, or out of the idea of an historical connection with the Teutones of the classice, is immaterial. Itis clear that the present word Daue-scd proves nothing respecting the Teutoucs. Perhaps, however, as esrly as the time of Martial the word Teutonicus was used in a general sense, denoting the Germane in general. Gertain it is that, before his time, it meant the particular people conquered by Marius, irrespective of origin or locality.-See Grimm's Deutsche Grammatih, i. p. 17, 3rd edit.
